[
  {
    "type": "EXPOSITORY (ENGLISH BIBLE)",
    "name": "Benson Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "Acts 25:18-19",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "Acts 25:18-19",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Against whom, when the accusers stood up ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— And offered what they had to say; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "they brought none accusation of such things as I supposed ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— From the general clamour they had made against him, as a seditious and dangerous person, they would have done. He had inferred, from the eagerness of their prosecution, and their urging the matter thus upon the Roman governors, one after another, 1st, That they had something to accuse him of, which was dangerous either to private property or to the public peace. Such were the outcries against the primitive Christians: so loud, so fierce, that the standers by, who judged of them by those outcries, could not but conclude that they were the worst of men; and, indeed, to represent them as such was the design of that clamour, as it was of that against our Saviour. 2d, That they had something to accuse him of that was cognizable in the Roman courts, and of which the governor was properly the judge; as Gallio expected, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 18:14",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Otherwise it was absurd and ridiculous to trouble him with it. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "But had certain questions ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Disputable matters; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "against him of their own superstition ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "religion ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "rather; for, as Agrippa was a Jew, and now came to pay a visit of respect to Festus on his arrival at his province, it is improbable that he would use so rude a word as one that properly signified superstition: so that this text affords a further argument that the word ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "δεισιδαιμονια ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "will admit a milder interpretation, as has been observed on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 17:22",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "and of one Jesus ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Thus does Festus speak of him to whom every knee shall bow; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "which was dead ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Or had been dead; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "whom Paul ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Unaccountably; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "affirmed to be alive ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "— Though, at the same time, he acknowledged that he had been crucified at Jerusalem, and expired on the cross. And was this a doubtful question? But why, O Festus, didst thou doubt concerning it? Only because thou didst not search into the evidence of it. Otherwise that evidence might have opened to thee till it had grown up into full conviction; and thy illustrious prisoner had led thee into the glorious liberty of the children of God! ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
